                    <persName corresp="#p_PEW1">Pauley</persName> Files</note>
                <head>No. 949<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Adviser on Administration and Political Science on the
                        United States Delegation to the Allied Commission on Reparations</hi>
                        (<persName corresp="#p_GLH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gulick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Representative on the Allied Commission on
                        Reparations</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PEW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pauley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-sibling-dates" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1945-07-29">Undated</date>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Additional evidence on German [<hi rend="italic"
                        >Soviet?</hi>] removals from Berlin.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(1)</label>
                    <item>We have three new reports on removals from Berlin. These are as follows: <list>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Report on <hi rend="italic">industrial removals</hi> from the <hi
                                    rend="italic">Russian sector</hi> observed on July 28 by
                                    <persName corresp="#p_SRG1">Sproul</persName>, <persName
                                    corresp="#p_ME1">Mahler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TS2"
                                    >Trone</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_JGH1"
                                    >Johnson</persName>.</item>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Report on <hi rend="italic">Art removals</hi> by USSR from <hi
                                    rend="italic">US sector</hi> by <persName corresp="#p_BJN1">John
                                    Nicholas Brown</persName> for the US Group, Control Council,
                                    <gloss target="#t_RDR1">RD &amp; R</gloss> Div. as of July
                                29.</item>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">c</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Report on removals of <hi rend="italic">property belonging to US
                                    citizens</hi> and Neutrals from <hi rend="italic">US
                                sector</hi>, as of July 29, by <persName corresp="#p_RCAD1">Capt.
                                    Arthur D. Reed</persName> for <gloss target="#t_G51"
                                >G–5</gloss>, Berlin District.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>(2)</label>
                    <item>New material in these reports is as follows: <list>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Removal of raw materials, scrap and cable machinery, including
                                wire twisters and insulation weaving machines, is reported from the
                                Russian sector, also domestic sewing machines.</item>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                            <item>Most of the public Art collections of Berlin were apparently
                                stored for protection in the <hi rend="italic">Flakturm</hi> at the
                                Zoo, and in four buildings in the US–<gloss target="#t_UK1"
                                    >UK</gloss> Sectors of Berlin. The distinctive and valuable
                                material has been removed by the Russians, including especially the
                                sculptures, paintings, antiquities, art libraries, and German <hi
                                    rend="italic">Volk</hi> arts. The removals were selective, much
                                material of second rate importance remains.</item>
                            <label>(<hi rend="italic">c</hi>)</label>
                            <item>The <persName corresp="#p_RCAD1">Reed</persName> report lists 20
                                American owned plants and installations which have been removed 20%
                                to 100%. These are:</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
